      • accumulating

        Or<G,Every<B>> accumulating()
        Converts this Or to an Or with the same Good type and a Bad type consisting of One parameterized by this Or's Bad type.

        For example, invoking the accumulating method on an Or<Int,ErrorMessage> would convert it to an Or<Int,One<ErrorMessage>>. This result type, because the Bad type is an Every, can be used with the mechanisms provided in class Accumulation to accumulate errors.

        Note that if this Or is already an accumulating Or, the behavior of this accumulating method does not change. For example, if you invoke accumulating on an Or<Int,One<ErrorMessage>> you will be rewarded with an Or<Int,One<One<ErrorMessage>>>. 

         Scalactic: def accumulating: Or[G, One[B]]
        Returns:
        this Good, if this Or is a Good; or this Bad value wrapped in a One if this Or is a Bad.

        boolean exists(Predicate<? super G> p)
        Returns true if this Or is a Good and the predicate p returns true when applied to this Good's value.

        Note: The exists method will return the same result as forAll(java.util.function.Predicate<? super G>) if this Or is a Good, but the opposite result if this Or is a Bad. 

        Scalactic: def exists(p: (G) => Boolean): Boolean
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        the result of applying the passed predicate p to the Good value, if this is a Good, else false

      • filter

        Or<G,B> filter(Function<G,Validation<B>> validator)
        Returns this Or if either 1) it is a Bad or 2) it is a Good and applying the validation function validation to this Good's value returns Pass; otherwise, returns a new Bad containing the error value contained in the Fail resulting from applying the validation function validation to this Good's value.

        For examples of filter used in for expressions, see the main documentation for interface Validation. 

        Scalactic: def filter[C >: B](f: (G) => Validation[C]): Or[G, C]
        Parameters:
        validator - the validation function to apply
        Returns:
        a Good if this Or is a Good that passes the validation function, else a Bad.

        boolean forAll(Predicate<? super G> p)

        Note: The forAll(java.util.function.Predicate<? super G>) method will return the same result as exists(java.util.function.Predicate<? super G>) if this Or is a Good, but the opposite result if this Or is a Bad.

        Returns:

      • toEither

        Either<B,G> toEither()
        Returns an Either: a Right containing the Good value, if this is a Good; a Left containing the Bad value, if this is a Bad.

        Note that values effectively switch sides when converting an Or to an Either. If the type of the Or on which you invoke toEither() is Or<Int,ErrorMessage> for example, the result will be an Either<ErrorMessage,Int>. The reason is that the convention for Either is that Left is used for bad values and Right is used for good ones. 

        Scalactic: def toEither: Either[B, G]
        Returns:
        this Good value, wrapped in a Right, or this Bad value, wrapped in a Left.

      • toTry

        Try<G> toTry()
        Returns a Try: a Success containing the Good value, if this is a Good; a Failure containing the Bad value, if this is a Bad.

        Note: If the Bad type of this Or is not a subclass of Throwable (or Throwable itself) the cause of the Failure will be a IllegalArgumentException containing as message the string value of the Bad. 

        Scalactic: def toTry(implicit ev: <:<[B, Throwable]): Try[G]
        Returns:
        this Good value, wrapped in a Success, or this Bad value, wrapped in a Failure.
